1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Bf4 Bb4!? { Although black has many choices on move 5 (c6, dxc4, Be7) this option seems to lead to the most interesting and dynamic positions while giving many opportunities for an unprepared opponent to face early problems } 6. e3 { The most natural and popular move } (6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. Qa4 (8. e3?! b5 $15 { White is not winning back the pawn }) 8... O-O { unpinning the d7-knight and threatening Nb6 } 9. Qxc4 c5 { leading to a fascinating line where black sacrifices a pawn and potentially the exchange } 10. dxc5 b6 11. Bd6 (11. c6 Nc5 12. Rd1 Nd5) (11. cxb6 Nxb6 12. Qd4 Bb7 $44) 11... Nxc5 12. Bxf8 Qxf8 $44) 6... c5 7. a3 (7. cxd5?! { Is only asking for troubule } 7... Nxd5 $40) (7. Bd3 cxd4 { Black is happy to liquidate the center and leave white with an isolated pawn } 8. exd4 (8. Nxd4?? e5) 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nb6 10. Bd3 Nbd5 11. Bd2 O-O 12. O-O b6 { 0-1 (46) Santos,J (2361)-Warmerdam,M (2610) Chennai 2022 }) (7. Be2 { This line is slightly different from 7.Bd3 as black can't forcibly give white an isolated pawn since white's queen is not blocked by the bishop. However black can still attain a solid and pleasant position } 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O 9. O-O (9. a3 { This is basically a loss of time. Black will now seize the initiative } 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Nb6 $15 11. Bd3 c4 12. Bc2 Nfd5 $15) 9... Nb6 10. Bd3 cxd4 11. exd4 Nbd5) 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Qa5 9. Qb3 (9. Qc2) 9... O-O 10. Bd3 (10. Be2 b6 11. O-O Ba6 $15) 10... b5!! $40 11. Qxb5 Qxc3+ 12. Ke2 a6 13. Qa4 (13. Qb1 dxc4) 13... cxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd3+ *


