1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bd7!? { Already an off-beat move to avoid mainline opening theory. The idea of this move will become clear very soon... } 4. Nf3 a6 { Preparing to trade off our bad bishop for white's good bishop! It is not easy for white to effectively stop this plan } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gd7b5] } 5. Bd3 (5. Nc3 { This prevents Bb5 but makes c5 stronger since white cannot reply with c3 } 5... c5 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. Bf4 Nge7 9. O-O Qc7 { [%cal Gh7h6,Gg7g5,Ge8c8] }) (5. b3 c5 { This is an improved version of the of the mainline French since b3 is not useful for white. }) (5. a4 c5 { This is an improved version of the of the mainline French since a4 is not useful for white and actually weakens the b4 square }) (5. c4 dxc4 { This leads to a pleasant transformation for black... } 6. Bxc4 Bc6 { All of a sudden, the "bad" French bishop is now black's best piece! } { [%cal Gc6g2] } 7. O-O Nd7 { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gd7b6,Gg8e7,Ge7f5,Gf8e7] } 8. Nc3 Nb6 9. Bb3 Ne7 10. Be3 Nf5 { very harmonious setup for black! } { [%cal Gf8e7,Gd8d7,Ge8c8,Gh7h6,Gg7g5] }) 5... Bb5 6. Bxb5+ axb5 { Black should be quite happy to achieve these doubled b-pawns on the queenside. They are not at all weak (as long as black doesn't play c5), and black is happy to have the half-open file for the rook. } { [%cal Ga8a2] } 7. O-O Nd7 { The following line will demonstrate black's optimal setup and plan heading into the middle game } 8. c3 Nb6 9. Nbd2 Ne7 10. Re1 Nf5 { [%cal Gg7g5,Gg5g4,Gf8e7,Gh7h5,Gc7c6,Ge8d7] } 11. b3 c6 12. Bb2 (12. Nf1 Be7) 12... Be7 13. Nf1 g5 { [%csl Rc4][%cal Gg5g4,Gh7h5,Ge8d7,Gd8g8,Gg8g6,Gb5c4,Gd5c4] } *


