1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Bb4! { It's best to pin the knight as soon as black has the chance. Black intends to capture on c3 to damage white's queenside pawn structure. } 5. a3?! (5. Bg5 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 h6 7. Bh4? (7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. e3 b6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O { Black will likely be having all the fun in the middlegame. There are 2 plans between attacking on the kingside and playing positionally against white's double pawns on the queenside. } 10... O-O { [%csl Ga5,Rc4,Gg4][%cal Gb8c6,Gc6a5,Gg7g4,Gd7d6] }) 7... g5 8. Bg3 f4 { trapping the bishop }) (5. Bd2 b6 6. a3 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Bb7 8. e3 d6 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. O-O Ne4 11. Be1 O-O { [%csl Gg4,Rf3][%cal Gg7g5,Gg5g4,Gd8h4,Gb7g2] } (11... Qe7 { also possible to hold of on castling, and eventually castle queenside or put the king on f7. } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gg7g4] })) 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 { The following line will illustrate the optimal attacking setup for black... } 6... b6 7. e3 Bb7 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Re1 Ne4 11. Bb2 Qe7 { [%cal Gg7g5,Gg5g4,Gb7g2,Gd7f6,Ge8g8,Gh8f8,Gf8f6,Gf6h6] } 12. Bf1 O-O 13. Qc2 Rf6 14. a4 Rh6 { Black's attack is pretty much unstoppable } { [%cal Gg7g4,Ge7h4] } *


