1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. e4?! { This is a worse version of the famous Staunton Gambit, because the inclusion of e6 is more useful than the inclusion of c4. } (3. g4 { a rare gambit which black has a nice reply against... } 3... fxg4 4. h3 g3! { giving back the pawn to weaken white's kingside structure } 5. fxg3 c5! { black is having more fun! } { [%csl Rg3,Rd4][%cal Gd8c7,Gc7g3,Gc5d4,Gb8c6] }) 3... fxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 (5. Bg5 Bb4 6. f3 d5 7. fxe4 dxe4 { transposes to mainline }) 5... d5! 6. fxe4 dxe4 { The doubled e-pawns look ugly at first, but black's pawn on e4 restricts white's development and it is not easy for white to attack and win. Meanwhile, black enjoys the half-open d-file for the queen and white's pawn on d4 is a clear target. } 7. Bg5 Bb4 { [%cal Ge8g8,Gc7c5,Gb8c6] } *


