1. d4 c5 2. dxc5!? { A slightly offbeat line with an interesting idea in mind... } 2... e6 3. Nc3 Bxc5 4. Ne4! { The main point of this variation. White immediately puts the question to how black will deal with the threads of Nxc5 and Nd6+ } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Ge4c5,Ge4d6] } 4... Be7 { [%cal Ge4d6] } (4... d5!? { While this is an interesting move that a lot of players will try, it is not objectively great for black. } 5. Nxc5 Qa5+ 6. c3 Qxc5 7. e4! $14 { A strong reply! White temporarily sacrifices a pawn to open the position as quickly as possible and make use of the bishop pair. Here's one common example variation of how play can proceed... } 7... dxe4 8. Qg4 { [%csl Gg7,Ge4][%cal Gg4e4,Gg4g7] } 8... Qe5 9. Bf4 Qf6 10. Bxb8 { In this case, it's worth making this trade to take away black's castling rights and to win back the pawn on e4. } 10... Rxb8 11. Bb5+ Kf8 12. Qxe4 $14 { [%csl Rf8][%cal Gg1f3,Ge1c1] }) (4... Nf6 { This is objectively the best move, but only played 8% of the time in the lichess database. The resulting position will be roughly equal and playable for both sides } 5. Nxc5 Qa5+ 6. Qd2!? { I didn't know this move even existed, until making this file. Perhaps it's the best way to fight for a small edge... } 6... Qxc5 7. Qg5 Qxg5 8. Bxg5 $10 { Engine gives +0.1 and there are many ways for this position to branch out. I'd slightly prefer white with the bishop pair. }) 5. Nd6+ Bxd6 6. Qxd6 Qe7 7. Qxe7+ Nxe7 8. e4 $14 { White is slightly better with the bishop pair, more space, and an easy-to-play middlegame } *


