[Event "Eastern Class Championships"]
[Site "Sturbridge, MA"]
[Date "2014.03.15"]
[White "Kamsky, Gata"]
[Black "Shankland, Sam"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2709"]
[BlackElo "2611"]
[Annotator "Rosen,Eric"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A45"]
[Opening "Indian Defense: Accelerated London System"]
[StudyName "London Opening | Games you Should Know by Heart"]
[ChapterName "Kamsky, Gata - Shankland, Sam"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/FErc0llB/E3YZP7nj"]

{ In this game, GM Gata Kamsky who is considered a London specialist uncorked
some beautiful opening preparation to easily takedown GM Sam Sam Shankland.
This is one of the games that inspired me to add the London to my opening
repertoire }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Nd2 c5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Ngf3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3 { Perhaps the most common "mainline" in the London } 8... Qe7 { preparing e5 } 9. Ne5! { preventing e5 } 9... Nd7 10. Nxd7 Bxd7?! (10... Qxd7! { key move
which is impossible to play without understanding the tactical nuances } 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 g6 16. Qg5 { only move to force a draw. Everything else loses } (16. Nxc5 gxh5 { Compare this
to what happened in the game, there would be a bishop to capture on d7 and
white would be happy. In this case, white is sad. })) 11. Bxd6 { The beginning
of a beautiful tactical sequence } 11... Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 (12... Qc7!? $14 { The best move, but hard to figure out. }) 13. Bxh7+!! Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4! Qc4 16. Ng5 Rfd8 17. Qxf7+ Kh8 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Rd1! { A nice idea. White
foresees the black king trying to escape via d6 and makes sure the rook is
optimized for attack } 19... e5 20. Qf7+ Kh8 21. e4 Ne7 { giving back the piece, but
what else to do? } 22. Qxe7 Bb5 23. Rd2 Qxa2 24. Qf7 Qa1+ 25. Rd1 Qxb2 26. Qh5+ Kg8 27. Qh7+ Kf8 28. Qh8+ Ke7 29. Qxg7+ Kd6 30. Rxd5+ Kc6 31. Qf6+ { 1-0 Black resigns. } (31. Kc7 Ne6+ $18) 1-0


