1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 e6 6. Ngf3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bb5 Ne7 { The most common move, but probably not the best. Black's attempts to make
white's bishop meaningless on b5, but white is happy retreat to d3 and
question the placement of black's knight on e7 } 9. Bd3 b6 10. e4! { Somewhat
paradoxical, but very strong. It is generally not a great idea to open the
center when your opponent has casstled and you haven't. However, white's
central thrust is justified as there are several tactical targets for black to
be concerned about (a8, d6, f6, and h7). } 10... dxe4 (10... Bxg3 11. hxg3 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Ng6 13. Ne5! $16) 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Rb8 13. dxc5! { maintaining
intiative and essentially winning a pawn. Black is now forced to trade on g3
and open the h-file for white. } 13... Bxg3 14. hxg3 (14. Qxd8 Bxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Rxd8 { [%cal Gc5c6] } 16. c6) 14... f5? { losing tactically } (14... Qxd1+ 15. Kxd1 f5 16. Bd3 bxc5 17. Kc2 $16 { the best line for black, but a
very nice positional game for white }) 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 { [#] White to move and win! } 16. c6! { extremely powerful intermediate move } 16... Nd5 17. Bxd5 Rxd5 18. Rd1 Rxd1+ 19. Kxd1 $18 { black's position is hopeless. White's extra pawn on c6 is
extremely dangerous and will be well supported with Ne5 } 19... Ba6 20. Ne5 Rc8 21. c4 b5 22. b4 bxc4 23. a4 Rd8+ 24. Kc2 Rd5 25. f4 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


