1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nbd7 5. e3 (5. cxd5 exd5 6. Nxd5?? { The elephant trap! } 6... Nxd5 7. Bxd8 Bb4+ 8. Qd2 Bxd2+ 9. Kxd2 Kxd8 $19) 5... c6 6. Nf3 Qa5 { The start of the Cambridge Springs -- an aggressive and playable line against d4 mainlines. At the highest levels, the Cambridge Springs isn't as popular since white is slightly better in the mainlines. However, this can be a very effective weapon at the sub-master level as many players will fall victim to black's early initiative. Black plans to quickly increase the pressure with Ne4 and Bb4 } 7. Nd2 { Slightly unusual looking, but probably the best approach for white } (7. Bd3? { A natural looking move which simply loses material } 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 Ne4 { Forked! } { [%csl Rg5,Rc3][%cal Ge4g5,Ge4c3,Ga5g5,Ga5c3] } 9. Bf4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qxc3+ 11. Nd2 Bb4) (7. c5?! Ne4 8. Qc2 b6 $36) (7. cxd5 Nxd5 { Keeping the 5th-rank open and pressure the knight on c3 } 8. Rc1 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba3 10. Rc2 b6 { Planning to trade off the bad bishop for white's good bishop } { Gelfand, Boris - Carlsen, Magnus, 0-1, FIDE Candidates, 2013, https://lichess.org/KrEw3E6R } { [%cal Gc8a6] }) (7. Qc2 Ne4 8. Bf4 Bb4 9. Rc1 Qxa2 { A common theme in this line. Black is now ready to trade queens by capturing on c3 }) 7... Bb4 8. Qc2 O-O 9. Be2 (9. Bd3? dxc4 { Winning material } { [%cal Gc4d3,Ga5g5] }) 9... dxc4 10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. Nxc4 Qc7 12. O-O b6 { Black has less space, but a very clear plan of Bb7 and an eventual c5. } { [%cal Gc8b7,Ga8d8,Gc6c5] } *


[Event "How to play against 1.d4: Neutralize the London System"]
[Date "2018.08.14"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D00"]
