1. Nf3 { [%clk 1:30:55] } (1. e4) 1... d5 { [%clk 1:30:37] } 2. g3 { [%clk 1:31:18] } 2... Bg4 { A small surprise on move 2! I've never played this before in a serious game. A month before the tournament, I stumbled upon this video: https://youtu.be/N9CNJA2S-uE?si=Rkg2heV7IOcryd1f and I was inspired to try out this opening. } { [%clk 1:30:54] } (2... Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 { My usual reply to the KIA }) 3. Bg2 { [%clk 1:27:33] } 3... e6 { [%clk 1:31:10] } 4. c4 { [%clk 1:27:34] } 4... c6 { [%clk 1:30:23] } 5. O-O { [%clk 1:24:36] } (5. cxd5 cxd5 (5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 cxd5) 6. Qa4+) 5... Nf6 { [%clk 1:30:45] } 6. Qb3 { [%csl Rb7][%cal Gb3b7] [%clk 1:22:23] } 6... Qb6 { [%clk 1:29:59] } 7. d3 { [%clk 1:22:34] } (7. Qxb6 axb6) 7... Nbd7 { [%clk 1:29:42] } 8. Be3 { [%clk 1:12:02] } 8... Bc5 { This was pretty much the extent of my preparation } { [%csl Gg8][%cal Ge8g8] [%clk 1:29:16] } (8... Qxb3 9. axb3 a5 { also playable }) 9. Bxc5 { [%clk 1:06:22] } 9... Nxc5 { [%csl Gb3] [%clk 1:28:56] } 10. Qc2 { [%clk 1:06:11] } (10. Qxb6 axb6 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 { [%csl Ga2][%cal Ga8a1] } 12... Nb3 { [%csl Ga1] }) 10... O-O { [%clk 1:19:25] } (10... Bxf3!? 11. Bxf3 d4 { should have considered this }) 11. Nbd2 { [%clk 1:06:35] } 11... a5 { [%clk 1:17:54] } 12. Rfc1 { [%clk 1:05:17] } (12. a3 a4) 12... Ncd7 { [%clk 1:17:14] } 13. b3 { [%clk 1:04:40] } 13... Rfe8 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge6e5] [%clk 1:15:52] } 14. e3 { [%clk 0:48:34] } 14... e5 { [%csl Ge5,Gd5] [%clk 1:10:34] } 15. cxd5 { [%clk 0:46:35] } 15... cxd5 { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gc2c7] [%clk 0:57:05] } (15... Nxd5 16. Nc4 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc4b6,Gc4e5] } 16... Qc7 { [%cal Ga2a3] } 17. a3 { Didn't want to enter this structure -- it seems easier to play for white } { [%csl Gb4,Ge5][%cal Ga1b1,Gb3b4,Gc2b2,Gb2e5] }) 16. h3 { [%csl Gh3] [%clk 0:42:01] } 16... Bf5 { [%clk 0:47:59] } 17. g4 { [%clk 0:39:46] } 17... Bxd3 { Even though this perhaps is objectively not the best, I thought it led to an easier position to play and understand from the black side. } { [%clk 0:37:00] } (17... Be6 { I had a hard time evaluating this move during the game. I didn't want to give white initiative with Qc7 and g5 ideas. }) (17... Bg6 18. g5 Nh5 { [%csl Rh5] } 19. Qc7 $14 { white appears to be in control } { [%csl Gc7,Ge5,Rd5,Gh4][%cal Gc1c7,Gg2d5,Gf3h4] }) 18. Qxd3 { [%clk 0:40:08] } 18... e4 { [%clk 0:37:26] } 19. Qd4 { [%clk 0:40:06] } 19... exf3 { [%clk 0:37:42] } 20. Qxb6 { [%clk 0:40:30] } 20... Nxb6 { [%clk 0:38:08] } 21. Nxf3 { [%csl Rd5] [%clk 0:39:51] } 21... Rec8 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f8,Gf8d6] [%clk 0:37:21] } 22. Nd4 { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gg2d5] [%clk 0:38:15] } 22... Kf8 { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gg4g5] [%clk 0:33:42] } 23. f3?! { [%clk 0:37:28] } (23. g5! Nfd7 24. Ne2 { The best way for white to fight for an edge according to the engine } { [%csl Gf4,Rd5,Gd1][%cal Ge2f4,Gc1d1] }) 23... Rxc1+ { [%clk 0:30:10] } 24. Rxc1 { [%clk 0:37:56] } 24... Rc8 { [%clk 0:30:22] } 25. Rb1 { [%clk 0:33:13] } 25... g6 { [%clk 0:29:02] } (25... Ke7 { [%csl Gf5,Gg7][%cal Gd4f5] }) 26. Bf1 { [%clk 0:32:48] } 26... Ke7 { [%clk 0:28:44] } 27. Kf2 { [%clk 0:32:56] } 27... Nfd7 { [%clk 0:26:07] } 28. g5 { [%clk 0:29:21] } 28... Nc5 { [%csl Gc5,Ge6,Rd4][%cal Gc5e6] [%clk 0:25:26] } 29. h4 { [%clk 0:26:46] } 29... Ne6 { [%clk 0:23:14] } 30. Bd3 { [%clk 0:26:16] } 30... Nd7 { I offered a draw here because I honestly thought the position was quite equal and I wasn't feeling that great. It was the second round of the day and I was feeling a bit lethargic during this game. It was also quite hot in the playing hall so I didn't want to suffer. After a few minutes, my opponent accepted the draw.
Take aways: The downside of playing an "opening surprise" is that I lack experience in some of the resulting structures. Despite getting the early time advantage in this game, I didn't fully understand what to do in the middle game. } { [%clk 0:22:00] } *


