1. d4 { [%clk 1:30:58] } 1... d5 { [%clk 1:30:46] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:31:22] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 3. Nc3 { [%clk 1:31:46] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 1:31:16] } 4. cxd5 { [%clk 1:32:07] } 4... exd5 { [%clk 1:31:39] } 5. Bg5 { [%clk 1:32:33] } 5... c6 { [%clk 1:32:06] } 6. e3 { [%clk 1:32:59] } 6... Be7 { [%clk 1:32:13] } 7. Bd3 { [%clk 1:33:10] } 7... Nbd7 { [%clk 1:32:20] } (7... h6 8. Bh4 Bg4 { I played this line against my opponent in the Biel Blitz. He was well prepared, so I didn't want to enter the same line in this game. }) 8. Nge2 { [%clk 1:31:18] } 8... h6 { [%clk 1:32:30] } 9. Bh4 { [%clk 1:31:42] } 9... O-O { [%clk 1:32:39] } 10. O-O { [%clk 1:31:52] } 10... Nh5 { The main point of black's setup. This forces the trade of DSBs and results in a relatively solid position. } { [%clk 1:32:23] } 11. Bxe7 { [%clk 1:30:50] } 11... Qxe7 { [%clk 1:32:49] } 12. Qd2 { [%clk 1:23:05] } 12... Re8 { [%clk 1:32:07] } 13. Rae1 { [%clk 1:18:56] } 13... Nf8 { [%clk 1:31:48] } 14. Nf4!? { An interesting idea, imbalancing the position and taking me out of my pre-game prep } { [%clk 1:07:56] } (14. Nc1 { I was mainly prepared for this move, white's idea being f3 and e4. }) 14... Nxf4 { [%clk 1:27:45] } 15. exf4 { [%clk 1:06:06] } 15... Qd8 { [%clk 1:28:04] } 16. Rxe8 { [%clk 0:58:15] } 16... Qxe8 { [%clk 1:26:25] } 17. Re1 { [%clk 0:58:39] } 17... Qd8 { [%clk 1:26:31] } 18. f5 { [%clk 0:57:39] } 18... Bd7 { [%clk 1:22:37] } 19. Re5 { [%clk 0:46:16] } 19... f6? { Probably the game losing move. In the moment, I didn't realize how harmful this move is to black's position. } { [%clk 1:09:46] } (19... Be8 { Looks ugly, but definitely a better approach. } { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gf8d7] }) 20. Re3 { From this point forward, white plays a positional masterclass } { [%clk 0:39:14] } 20... Qb6 { [%clk 1:09:08] } 21. Ne2 { [%clk 0:37:16] } 21... Re8 { [%clk 1:06:38] } 22. Rg3 { [%clk 0:34:06] } 22... Kh8 { [%clk 0:54:30] } 23. h4 { [%clk 0:24:23] } 23... Re7 { [%clk 0:52:51] } 24. Bb1 { [%clk 0:24:47] } 24... Be8 { [%clk 0:49:48] } 25. Nf4 { [%clk 0:19:53] } 25... Bf7 { [%clk 0:48:37] } 26. Ng6+! { [%clk 0:19:09] } 26... Bxg6 { [%clk 0:27:11] } (26... Nxg6 { I rejected this line because of the following variation } 27. fxg6 Be8 (27... Bg8 { The engine's defensive choice, but this looks extremely ugly as there are so many cases where's black's bishop is completely stuck } 28. Bf5 $16) 28. Re3 Rxe3 29. Qxe3 Qd8 { White to move and fork } 30. Qa3! $18) 27. fxg6 { [%clk 0:19:37] } 27... Qd8 { [%clk 0:27:18] } 28. Re3 { [%clk 0:16:57] } 28... Nd7 { [%clk 0:25:28] } 29. Bf5 { [%clk 0:15:21] } 29... Kg8 { [%clk 0:20:32] } 30. Rxe7 { [%clk 0:09:19] } 30... Qxe7 { [%clk 0:20:57] } 31. Qf4 { [%clk 0:09:45] } 31... Nf8 { [%clk 0:17:03] } 32. Qb8 { [%clk 0:07:25] } 32... a5 { [%clk 0:06:33] } 33. Qa8 { [%clk 0:07:27] } 33... a4 { [%clk 0:05:23] } 34. g3 { [%clk 0:06:41] } 34... Qb4 { [%clk 0:01:20] } 35. a3 { [%clk 0:05:03] } 35... Qe1+ { [%clk 0:01:23] } 36. Kg2 { [%clk 0:06:22] } 36... Qe7 { [%clk 0:01:35] } 37. h5 { [%clk 0:03:27] } 37... c5 { [%clk 0:00:49] } 38. dxc5 { [%clk 0:03:50] } 38... Qxc5 { [%clk 0:00:39] } 39. Qxb7 { [%clk 0:03:59] } 39... d4 { [%clk 0:00:35] } 40. Be4 { [%clk 0:03:27] } 40... Kh8 { [%clk 0:00:36] } 41. Bd5 { [%clk 0:01:44] } 41... d3 { [%clk 0:26:21] } 42. Qf7 { [%clk 0:31:43] } 42... Ne6 { Never resign when you have stalemate tricks! } { [%clk 0:26:47] } 43. Qxe6 { [%clk 0:29:51] } 43... Qf8 { [%clk 0:27:06] } 44. Qe3 { [%clk 0:30:01] } (44. Qg8+?? Qxg8 45. Bxg8 d2 { one way white could lose }) 44... f5 { [%clk 0:27:08] } 45. Qxd3 { [%clk 0:29:57] } 45... f4 { [%clk 0:27:33] } 46. Qa6 { [%clk 0:29:54] } 46... fxg3 { [%clk 0:25:42] } 47. Qa8 { A great game from my opponent and a slightly painful but valuable lesson for me. } { [%clk 0:30:17] } (47. fxg3 Qf1+) *


