1. d4 g6 2. e4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c6 { I was prepared for many different types of sideilnes for this game (see Doughtery prep file for lots of fun lines), but didn't look at 3...c6. From this point, the only opening prep I had was the brief analysis I did several months ago after I played Hikaru in the same line. } { [%csl Gc6] } (3... c5 4. dxc5 Qa5 5. Bd2 Qxc5 6. Nd5 b6 7. Bb4 Qc6 8. Bb5 Qb7 9. Qf3 $16 { one of the fun lines I was prepping }) 4. Nf3 d5 5. h3 dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nd7 (6... Nf6 7. Nxf6+ exf6 8. Bd3 { This is what I vaguely remembered preparing for Hikaru. }) (6... Bf5 7. Ng3 { [%csl Gc8,Gd7][%cal Gf5c8] }) 7. Bc4 Ndf6 (7... Ngf6 { More natural of course, but black has to be
ready for some scary lines... } { [%csl Re4] } 8. Neg5!? (8. Nxf6+ { safe/solid option } 8... Nxf6 9. O-O $14) 8... O-O (8... e6 9. Nxf7 Kxf7 10. Ng5+ Ke8 11. Nxe6) 9. Nxf7 Rxf7 10. Ng5 { I had calculated this during the game, but missed Nd5. The position is still interesting though } 10... Nd5 11. Nxf7 Kxf7 $13) 8. Ng3 { A novelty according to the database. While the knight isn't so useful on g3, it does avoid trades for the moment which is one of white's goals due to the space advantage. } (8. Nc5!? { Top stockfish choice which I didn't seriously consider }) 8... Nh6 9. c3 O-O (9... Nf5 10. Nxf5 Bxf5 11. Qb3 { [%csl Rb7,Rf7][%cal Gb3f7] }) 10. Ne5 { The idea to prevent Nf5 } 10... Nd5 { [%csl Gd5] } (10... Nf5? 11. Nxf5 Bxf5 12. Qb3 { [%csl Rf7,Rb7] }) 11. O-O Nf5 12. Nxf5 Bxf5 $14 { Although black has successfully traded off the "dumb" knight, the position is still pleasant for white. I was pleased to have a pleasant space advantage with relatively risk-free play } { [%csl Gd1,Gc1,Ga1,Gf1] } 13. Qf3 Qd6 14. Re1 Rae8 15. Bb3 Bc8 { lol, but what else to do for black? It's not easy to find a clear plan! } (15... f6) 16. c4 { [%csl Gb6][%cal Gd5b6] } 16... Nf6 (16... c5) (16... Nb6 17. c5) 17. Be3 { [%csl Gb3,Ge3,Ge5] } 17... Bf5 18. Rad1 Nd7 { [%csl Gd7][%cal Ge5d7] } 19. Ng4 Bxg4 (19... a6 20. Nh6+ Bxh6 (20... Kh8 21. Nxf5) 21. Bxh6 { [%csl Gf8][%cal Gh6f8] }) 20. hxg4 Qc7 21. Bf4 Qb6 22. Qg3 { a sneaky move which set up a few landmines... } (22. c5) 22... c5?? { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gc6c5] } (22... Bxd4? 23. Rxd4 Qxd4 24. Rd1) (22... a5 23. c5 Qa6 24. a4) 23. Ba4! { Conclusions: Playing patiently and prophylactically while applying gradual pressure can cause opponents to crumble! This game had similar vibes to my first round game. Improvements: Similar to the Adhiban game, I should be ready and confident against opening sidelines that I often encounter in blitz -- Not only knowing some opening ideas, but also understanding the middlegame structures and finding a few model games for inspiration. } (23. Rd8 Bc7 $18) 23... Rd8 (23... Qd8 { [%csl Gd8,Gd7,Ge8,Gf8,Ge7,Gf7,Gg7,Gg8][%cal Gd8e8] } 24. dxc5 { [%csl Rd8,Rd7,Re8][%cal Gd1d8,Ga4e8] }) 24. Bc7 { [%cal Gc7b6,Gc7d8] } *


