1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 { This opening definitely had some surprise value as my opponent took some time before playing c4 } 5. c4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 { [%csl Ge4,Gc4] } 7. Nc3 d6 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Bd7 10. Rc1 { a less common, but completely playable move that took me out of my opening prep } (10. f4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. Bf3 Nd7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qd4+ f6 { This was my pre-game opening preparation and f6 is Leela's top choice. }) 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 { [%csl Re4,Gd7,Rd4,Rg7,Gc5,Ga5,Rc4][%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5,Gd8a5,Gf8c8,Ga8c8] } (11... Bh6!? { a move that didn't even cross my mind. This is perhaps one reason Rc1isn't played so early for white in the Maroczy Bind } { [%csl Gh6,Gc1][%cal Gh6c1] } 12. Rc2 e5 13. Be3 Bxe3 { [%csl Ge3] } 14. fxe3 { [%csl Ge4] }) (11... Qa5 12. f4) 12. f4 (12. f3 a5 (12... Nd7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qd4+)) 12... Nd7 (12... Nxe4 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Qd4+ { [%cal Gd1d4] }) 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qd4+ { [%csl Gf6,Gg8][%cal Gf7f6,Gg7g8,Ge7e5] } 14... Kg8 (14... f6 { I didn't go for this because of the prospect of Bg4 and my light squares seemed too weak }) (14... e5 15. Qxd6 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 Qxb2 17. fxe5 Rae8) 15. Nd5 Bxd5 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc4d5] } 16. exd5 (16. cxd5 { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gc1c8] } 16... Qb6 17. Qxb6 axb6 18. Rc7 Nc5 { Based on my calculations during the game, I thought black had good chances to play for an advantange here } { [%csl Re4,Ra2] }) 16... Qb6 17. Qxb6 axb6 18. a3 Nc5 { [%csl Gb4,Ra3][%cal Gb2b4,Ga8a3] } 19. Rf3! { a strong and multi-purpose move which I had for some reason overlooked during the game } 19... Rfc8 20. Re3 Kf8 { [%csl Re7] } 21. Rh3 { [%cal Gf8g7,Gf8g8] } 21... Kg7 (21... h5 22. f5 { during the game, I wanted to avoid this position, but later realized this is probably fine for black since the knight can maneuver to e5 } { [%csl Rg6,Rh5][%cal Gc1f1,Gf1f8] } 22... Nd7) 22. Re3 { [%csl Gf8][%cal Gg7f8] } 22... Rc7 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gc7e7] } 23. Bf1 h5 24. Rce1 Kf6 { [%csl Rf6,Gf5][%cal Gf4f5] } 25. h3?! (25. g3 { This should have been played without much thought -- it discourages a4, and prepares the eventual h3 g4. I wasn't entirely sure how I would proceed from here. } 25... Rac8 26. h3 { [%csl Gh4][%cal Gh5h4] } 26... h4 27. g4) 25... h4 { [%csl Rh4,Gg5][%cal Gg6g5,Gf4g5] } 26. Kf2 { [%csl Rh4][%cal Gf2f3,Gf3g4,Gg4h4] } 26... Re8 { [%csl Re7,Rf6] } 27. Kf3 g5!? { I hadn't spotted this positional idea until a few moves before I played g5. The point is to deflect the pawn away from f4 and maneuver the knight to e5 } { [%csl Rf4,Re5,Re3,Re1,Rf1][%cal Rf4e5,Gc5d7,Gd7e5,Gd6e5] } 28. Kg4 gxf4 29. Rf3 Rg8+ 30. Kxh4?? (30. Kxf4 { White's probably still okay here, but the position looks more fun to play as black } 30... Nd7 $15 { [%cal Gf4e3,Gf4e4] } 31. Ke3+ { [%csl Re1] } 31... Kg7 { [%csl Re7,Ge5][%cal Gd7e5] }) 30... e5 $19 31. dxe6 Nxe6 32. g3 (32. Rxe6+ fxe6 33. Rxf4+ Ke5) (32. g4 { [%csl Rg3][%cal Gh4g3,Gf4g3] } 32... Rh8#) 32... Rc5 { [%csl Rh4][%cal Gg8g2,Gc5h5] } 33. gxf4 (33. Rxe6+ fxe6 34. Rxf4+ Rf5) 33... Rh5+!! 34. Kxh5 Ng7+ { [%csl Rh4,Rg4][%cal Gh5g4,Gh5h4,Gg7f5] } 35. Kh4 (35. Kh6 Rh8#) 35... Nf5+ 36. Kh5 Rh8+ 37. Kg4 Rh4# { A feel good ending! Conclusions: It's worth reviewing the opening and seeing how to exactly deal with the less popular 10. Rc1. This is the risk with playing an opening I don't have so much experience in... sometime I don't fully understand the subtle nuances since I don't have
so much playing experience. } { [%csl Gh4] } *


