[Event "STAFFORD GAMBIT TIME: Facing the \"safe variation\""]
[Date "2020.11.02"]
[White "5.d3 w/ Early Be2 & h3"]
[Black "The \"Safe Variation\""]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Eric"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C42"]
[Opening "Petrov's Defense: Stafford Gambit"]
[StudyName "STAFFORD GAMBIT TIME"]
[ChapterName "Facing the \"safe variation\""]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/wNOa0Srd/3Lh34PGV"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nc6 4. Nxc6 dxc6 5. d3 Bc5 6. Be2 h5 { [%csl Gd3,Ge2,Gh2] } 7. h3 (7. Be3 Bxe3 8. fxe3 Ng4 9. Bxg4 hxg4) (7. Rf1) 7... Qd4!? 8. O-O (8. Be3?! { Played
by Carlsen (DrNykterstein on lichess.org) } 8... Qxb2 9. Nd2 Bxe3 10. fxe3 Qe5 11. Nf3 (11. O-O Bxh3) 11... Qg3+ 12. Kf1 h4! $146 { A nice positional idea --
Black clamps down on the g3 square and prepares the eventual maneuver of Nh5-g3 } (12... Bg4 { This tricky move was played against Carlsen, however, it allowed
white to neutrallize and achieve a comfortable position without much problem } 13. Qe1! (13. hxg4?? Nxg4) 13... Qxe1+ 14. Kxe1 Bxf3 15. gxf3 $16 { Carlsen
went on to grind down his opponent })) (8. Rf1 { Not too many humans will play
this. However, Anish Giri played it on lichess. If you encounter this, just
offer a draw and he will likely accept. } 8... Qd6 9. f4 (9. c3 Qh2 10. Bf3 Nh7 11. d4 Be7 12. Be3 Ng5 13. Bxg5 Bxg5 14. Nd2 h4 15. Qe2 Be6 16. O-O-O) 9... Qe7 10. e5 (10. Nc3 a5 11. Bf3 Ng4 12. hxg4 hxg4 13. Be2 Qh4+ 14. Kd2 Qg3) 10... Nd5 11. d4 Bb6 12. c4 Nb4 13. a3 (13. c5 Ba5 14. Kf2 Bf5) 13... Qh4+ 14. Rf2 Bxd4 $19) 8... Qd6! { My recommendation. I discovered this move only when
beginning to work on this course. There are so many landmines in this
variation and white has to basically walk a thin tightrope secure a clear
advantage. } (8... Ng4 { A risky altenative -- While this move is refuted by the
engine, it could still be worth trying in blitz/ bullet } 9. hxg4 hxg4 10. g3 { Unfortunately black's attack runs out of steam and white will have a decisive
advantage } (10. Bxg4?) 10... Qe5 11. Kg2 Bxf2 12. Kxf2 Rh2+ 13. Ke1 Qxg3+ 14. Kd2) 9. c3 (9. Nd2? { Looks like a safe attempt for white to prepare Nf3 and
defend the kingside. However, black has a sweet continuation... } 9... Qg3 { Surprise! Black takes full advantage of the pinned f2 pawn and has the simple
threat of Bxh3 } 10. Kh1 { Best move, but a sad move } 10... Bxf2 { Yoink! Black regains
the pawn and threatens the deadly and thematic Ng4 } 11. Nf3 Bxh3! { Credit to
Stockfish for finding this sequence... } 12. Rxf2 Ng4! 13. Qf1 Nxf2+ 14. Kg1 Ng4 15. Kh1 Rh6!! $19 16. Bxh6 gxh6 { There is now no good way to stop Ne3. }) (9. Be3? { One of the most popular moves on lichess. Black now has a nice
sequence... } 9... Bxe3 10. fxe3 Bxh3! 11. Qe1 (11. gxh3? { Walks into forced
mate... } 11... Qg3+ 12. Kh1 Qxh3+ 13. Kg1 Qg3+ 14. Kh1 Ng4 15. Bxg4 hxg4#) 11... Be6 $17) (9. Nc3? Bxh3! 10. gxh3 { Black now mates by force! } (10. Bf3 Be6 $17 { Black is better with still greating attacking prospects on the kingside. }) (10. d4 Bxd4 11. Nd5 Ng4 12. Bxg4 Bxf2+ 13. Rxf2 Bxg4 14. Bf4 Bxd1 15. Bxd6 cxd5 16. Bxc7 Bg4 17. exd5 f6) 10... Qg3+ 11. Kh1 Qxh3+ 12. Kg1 Bd6 $19 13. f4 Qg3+ 14. Kh1 Ng4 15. Bxg4 hxg4#) (9. Bf3 { The second best move for white according to the
engine. While the engine gives around +1 for white, there are still chances
for black to stir up counterplay } 9... Ng4!? 10. e5 { Similar to the mainline,
this is the only move that doesn't lose for white } 10... Nxe5 11. Re1 Be6 12. Bxh5 O-O-O $44 { While black is still down a pawn, there a lots of fighting chances
with the half-open h-file, better development and opposite side castling. }) 9... Ng4 { White now only has one move that secures a clear advantage. Out of
the 28 games in which this position has occurred on lichess (as of November
2020) the best move has only been played 3 times. } 10. e5! { A nice tactical
resource that saves white's kingside from complete destruction. } (10. hxg4?? hxg4 { Black is now mating by force! }) (10. Bxg4? hxg4 11. d4 Bb6 $44 12. Be3 gxh3 13. g3 h2+ 14. Kh1 Bh3 15. Re1 O-O-O) (10. g3?? Qxg3+ 11. Kh1 Qh2#) 10... Bxf2+ (10... Qxe5 { but this fails tactically to } 11. Bxg4 hxg4 12. Re1 $18) 11. Rxf2 Nxf2 12. exd6 Nxd1 13. dxc7 Nxb2 14. Bxb2 Kd7 { From 7...Qd4, this appears to be the worst-case scenario for black. White has
2 minor pieces for a rook in the endgame and an unquestionable advantage
(Engine says this is decisive for white, but I would argue there are practical
chances for black to survive in a speed game). If you encounter someone who
enters this line it is likely they are a grandmaster or extensively well
prepared with the engine. } 15. c4 f6 16. Bc1 g5 (16... Kxc7 17. Bf4+ { [%csl Gf4] }) 17. Bb2 { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gb2f6,Gh8h5,Gh8f8] } 17... Rh6 { [%csl Gf6,Gg5,Gh5,Ge4][%cal Gb1d2,Gd2e4] } *


