1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 (6. d4) 6... b5 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd2d4] } 7. Bb3 (7. d4? { Just doesn't work } { [%csl Ga4,Ge5][%cal Gb5a4,Gd4e5] } 7... bxa4 8. d5 Na5 9. Nxe5 O-O $19) 7... d6 8. d4 { The start of the Rosen Attack! (Named after Leon Rosen) https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leon_Rosen } 8... exd4 (8... Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. c3 dxc3) (8... O-O 9. c3 { This is now a transposition into the Yates Variation (which usually features 8.c3 and 9.d4) }) 9. Bd5 { [%csl Rc6,Rd4][%cal Gd5a8] } (9. Nxd4? Nxd4 10. Qxd4 c5) (9. c3?! { Doesn't lead to enough compensation according to the engine } 9... dxc3 10. Nxc3 O-O $15) 9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Ne5 11. Nxd4 O-O $15 { With 2 bishops and better piece harmony, black is probably slightly better here. More analysis required to see if this line is still viable for white } 12. a4 (12. Bf4?! Bb7 { Fressinet, Laurent - Kramnik, Vladimir, 0-1, Grand Prix du Senat, 2002, https://lichess.org/0sMAPhNp } { Things went south very quickly for White (partly because Kramnik is an absolute beast) }) 12... Bd7 13. Nc3 (13. f4 Ng6 14. f5 Ne5 15. Nc3) (13. axb5 axb5) 13... b4 14. Ne4 *


